1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:02,739
Now, who will be the winner...

2
00:00:02,740 --> 00:00:05,440
of the 1-on-1 Deathmatch?

3
00:00:07,680 --> 00:00:09,050
Will it be...

4
00:00:09,650 --> 00:00:11,520
Real Cheetos Cake,

5
00:00:12,080 --> 00:00:14,950
the dessert made by Contender Cho Song Ah?

6
00:00:15,090 --> 00:00:16,590
Will it be the Edison in Baking,

7
00:00:17,290 --> 00:00:21,230
Kwak Dong Uk's Sfogliatelle?

8
00:00:22,360 --> 00:00:24,660
I had a feeling I'd advance.

9
00:00:27,400 --> 00:00:28,530
I'm confident that I'd win.

10
00:00:32,440 --> 00:00:34,940
Who will advance to the semifinal round?

11
00:00:46,550 --> 00:00:48,619
Okay. Contender Kwak Dong Uk.

12
00:00:48,620 --> 00:00:50,920
- Congratulations on advancing. - Seriously.

13
00:00:51,290 --> 00:00:53,189
I want to thank Chef Cho.

14
00:00:53,190 --> 00:00:54,959
- It was an honor. - Sure.

15
00:00:54,960 --> 00:00:56,330
- Thank you. - Thank you.

16
00:00:56,960 --> 00:00:58,030
Thank you.

17
00:00:58,900 --> 00:01:00,130
I've survived another day.

18
00:01:00,430 --> 00:01:01,599
I think I passed...

19
00:01:01,600 --> 00:01:03,669
because mine was closer to the original Cheetos.

20
00:01:03,670 --> 00:01:05,869
I'm already worrying about what to prepare...

21
00:01:05,870 --> 00:01:07,270
for the next round.

22
00:01:07,370 --> 00:01:10,210
I'm confident. I have to be confident.

23
00:01:15,210 --> 00:01:16,749
You'll be over in two hours.

24
00:01:16,750 --> 00:01:17,849
- Me? - Yes.

25
00:01:17,850 --> 00:01:18,879
I'll be done quickly.

26
00:01:18,880 --> 00:01:19,880
- Exactly. - Yes.

27
00:01:19,881 --> 00:01:21,390
Let me know if you need help.

28
00:01:22,320 --> 00:01:23,320
I'll help you.

29
00:01:25,120 --> 00:01:27,630
We should get it done quickly, so we can get some rest.

30
00:01:28,930 --> 00:01:30,260
What I said made him laugh,

31
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:33,969
but he wouldn't treat me harshly when I'm young.

32
00:01:33,970 --> 00:01:36,430
He'll treat me kindly and leave kindly.

33
00:01:36,600 --> 00:01:39,099
Some chefs are more overrated than you think.

34
00:01:39,100 --> 00:01:42,310
I'd like to teach young chefs a lesson.

35
00:01:42,340 --> 00:01:44,939
"No matter how confident you are,"

36
00:01:44,940 --> 00:01:47,749
"you can't overlook one's experience."

37
00:01:47,750 --> 00:01:51,220
I'll choose Shield Two as my opponent.

38
00:01:51,550 --> 00:01:52,749
- Shield Two? - Yes.

39
00:01:52,750 --> 00:01:55,890
Cho Sang Min, the Five-Star Pastry Chef.

40
00:01:57,190 --> 00:02:00,119
I'll choose monaka.

41
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:01,329
- Monaka? - Yes.

42
00:02:01,330 --> 00:02:04,830
Contender Cho Sang Min chose monaka.

43
00:02:08,170 --> 00:02:10,670
Lee Kyung Mu took 2nd place in Round 2.

44
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:11,800
It was a team competition.

45
00:02:11,801 --> 00:02:13,339
- Yes, they fought as a team. - I see.

46
00:02:13,340 --> 00:02:14,409
It's a match between the 2nd-place team and the 1st.

47
00:02:14,410 --> 00:02:16,810
- It's the 2nd and the 1st. - Yes. They were high-ranked.

48
00:02:19,610 --> 00:02:20,610
Let's go.

49
00:02:30,120 --> 00:02:32,260
Well, do you like monaka?

50
00:02:32,590 --> 00:02:35,529
When I went to Grandma's house, I saw them in piles.

51
00:02:35,530 --> 00:02:38,029
They had red bean paste inside and were wrapped in plastic.

52
00:02:38,030 --> 00:02:40,630
- The original ones. - I had them a lot.

53
00:02:40,830 --> 00:02:45,339
In the past, monaka was the best gift...

54
00:02:45,340 --> 00:02:46,400
when visiting grandparents' place.

55
00:02:46,840 --> 00:02:49,209
Will it be easy to transform monaka, though?

56
00:02:49,210 --> 00:02:50,379
I think it'll be hard.

57
00:02:50,380 --> 00:02:53,139
That's why I thought they'd fill it with something else.

58
00:02:53,140 --> 00:02:55,309
But I see them making the shells from scratch.

59
00:02:55,310 --> 00:02:57,219
That won't be easy, though.

60
00:02:57,220 --> 00:03:01,089
The dough is made of glutinous rice,

61
00:03:01,090 --> 00:03:03,249
and it's shaped with a machine.

62
00:03:03,250 --> 00:03:05,519
I think they'll come up with a new shell...

63
00:03:05,520 --> 00:03:08,860
based on the interpretation of their own.

64
00:03:13,700 --> 00:03:16,300
We're seeing Cho Sang Min's chocolate crafting again.

65
00:03:17,470 --> 00:03:19,139
Are those hearts?

66
00:03:19,140 --> 00:03:20,199
- They're hearts. - I see.

67
00:03:20,200 --> 00:03:21,210
He's touching the women's hearts.

68
00:03:23,680 --> 00:03:26,040
- They're pretty. - I know. They're cute.

69
00:03:28,080 --> 00:03:30,620
There's an egg-shaped chocolate. When you break it,

70
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:32,950
there's a toy inside.

71
00:03:33,380 --> 00:03:36,090
Monaka is similar to that because it has a shell,

72
00:03:36,420 --> 00:03:38,760
and there's something inside.

73
00:03:39,020 --> 00:03:40,629
I thought it'd be fun...

74
00:03:40,630 --> 00:03:43,190
if one would break the shell to eat something.

75
00:03:44,960 --> 00:03:47,229
So, I coated the heart-shaped monaka shells...

76
00:03:47,230 --> 00:03:49,370
with chocolate.

77
00:03:51,070 --> 00:03:54,710
Then, I made the red-bean filling to put inside.

78
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:00,310
What's that now?

79
00:04:00,950 --> 00:04:02,050
It's molecular gastronomy.

80
00:04:02,480 --> 00:04:04,720
- That's molecular gastronomy. - It's part of molecular gastronomy.

81
00:04:07,520 --> 00:04:08,849
As it will be plated,

82
00:04:08,850 --> 00:04:10,620
he's using such elements...

83
00:04:10,860 --> 00:04:12,090
in a more refined way.

84
00:04:16,190 --> 00:04:18,060
When you crack open the monaka shell,

85
00:04:18,300 --> 00:04:21,070
I want the red-bean jellies to pour out.

86
00:04:22,170 --> 00:04:24,940
He's making caviar with red beans for the filling.

87
00:04:25,140 --> 00:04:26,240
Red-bean caviar?

88
00:04:26,970 --> 00:04:28,270
Will it taste like red beans, though?

89
00:04:28,710 --> 00:04:29,770
It looks like frogspawn.

90
00:04:35,610 --> 00:04:38,350
The monaka shells are coated with chocolate.

91
00:04:39,650 --> 00:04:41,449
It's a plated dessert...

92
00:04:41,450 --> 00:04:43,789
where you break the chocolate shell of the monaka...

93
00:04:43,790 --> 00:04:46,819
and enjoy the red-bean jelly...

94
00:04:46,820 --> 00:04:47,960
with matcha ice cream.

95
00:04:48,230 --> 00:04:49,890
As for Contender Cho Sang Min,

96
00:04:50,090 --> 00:04:52,559
I thought he'd only reinterpret the sweet paste.

97
00:04:52,560 --> 00:04:56,469
My strategy was to interpret it in a totally different way...

98
00:04:56,470 --> 00:04:58,970
to create a completely new product.

99
00:05:01,840 --> 00:05:02,910
What?

100
00:05:03,370 --> 00:05:04,780
He added beans.

101
00:05:05,240 --> 00:05:07,280
- Beans? - What kind of beans are they?

102
00:05:07,610 --> 00:05:09,009
They're cranberry beans.

103
00:05:09,010 --> 00:05:11,180
- What are cranberry beans? - Is there such a thing?

104
00:05:12,250 --> 00:05:13,920
Its pattern is similar to a tiger's.

105
00:05:15,350 --> 00:05:17,590
How do they taste?

106
00:05:17,920 --> 00:05:19,859
But as for the taste of the cranberry beans,

107
00:05:19,860 --> 00:05:21,730
it's not really special.

108
00:05:21,830 --> 00:05:24,730
Their texture and color are different than others.

109
00:05:24,900 --> 00:05:27,499
I think he's going for that difference.

110
00:05:27,500 --> 00:05:29,030
- It tastes like kidney beans. - Yes.

111
00:05:29,700 --> 00:05:31,740
Why do I hear a pressure cooker?

112
00:05:32,200 --> 00:05:33,240
Is someone cooking rice?

113
00:05:35,710 --> 00:05:37,839
I'm sure someone's cooking red beans.

114
00:05:37,840 --> 00:05:39,579
- Someone's cooking red beans. - Or boiling them.

115
00:05:39,580 --> 00:05:41,650
It's Contender Lee Kyung Mu.

116
00:05:45,620 --> 00:05:46,919
He's boiling the cranberry beans.

117
00:05:46,920 --> 00:05:48,990
It's because it takes too long to cook beans.

118
00:05:49,320 --> 00:05:50,420
You have to use a pressure cooker.

119
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:52,120
Why does he remove it already, though?

120
00:05:53,730 --> 00:05:55,790
- Is it too soon? - Hasn't it been only ten minutes?

121
00:05:56,330 --> 00:05:57,799
Are they cooked? What if they aren't?

122
00:05:57,800 --> 00:05:59,499
They aren't cooked. Maybe...

123
00:05:59,500 --> 00:06:01,399
he undercooked it...

124
00:06:01,400 --> 00:06:03,370
to maintain the popping texture.

125
00:06:09,470 --> 00:06:11,210
Is that what he's going to use?

126
00:06:11,910 --> 00:06:12,910
- Amazing. - Really?

127
00:06:12,910 --> 00:06:13,910
That's interesting.

128
00:06:15,780 --> 00:06:17,850
- Isn't it for grilling pork belly? - That one!

129
00:06:19,420 --> 00:06:21,420
- I see it often in shorts. - Yes.

130
00:06:21,520 --> 00:06:22,749
- It's automatic. - Is that real?

131
00:06:22,750 --> 00:06:23,890
Yes. It tosses the food automatically.

132
00:06:26,920 --> 00:06:28,759
People usually use it...

133
00:06:28,760 --> 00:06:30,389
to cook pork belly at home.

134
00:06:30,390 --> 00:06:33,769
But he was cooking beans in it.

135
00:06:33,770 --> 00:06:37,400
I thought it was a good idea.

136
00:06:37,570 --> 00:06:40,440
Something like that only comes from experience.

137
00:06:42,110 --> 00:06:43,409
Within the time limit,

138
00:06:43,410 --> 00:06:45,309
I have to work fast and simultaneously.

139
00:06:45,310 --> 00:06:48,680
I was worried about having to keep stirring it myself.

140
00:06:48,850 --> 00:06:52,520
It's a solution I came up with to solve the time issue.

141
00:06:53,520 --> 00:06:54,590
That's done.

142
00:06:55,720 --> 00:06:58,060
While they're cooking, I'll roll out the pie sheet.

143
00:06:58,620 --> 00:06:59,720
Good.

144
00:07:01,390 --> 00:07:02,660
While the sweet paste is cooking,

145
00:07:03,030 --> 00:07:04,560
I thought I'd roll out the pie sheet.

146
00:07:08,230 --> 00:07:10,030
The key is to get the texture of the monaka.

147
00:07:10,940 --> 00:07:12,169
I thought of...

148
00:07:12,170 --> 00:07:14,840
how to recreate the texture of the monaka with bread.

149
00:07:22,680 --> 00:07:25,150
The shell is crunchier than you think.

150
00:07:25,380 --> 00:07:27,590
Recreating that texture was the hardest part.

151
00:07:33,660 --> 00:07:34,790
Is it a pie dough?

152
00:07:35,490 --> 00:07:38,499
He's trying to make the monaka shells with it.

153
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,099
- I think so too. - Yes.

154
00:07:40,100 --> 00:07:42,399
Is the shell originally made of pie dough?

155
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:44,039
Making monaka with the pie dough?

156
00:07:44,040 --> 00:07:45,970
It sounds too heavy to me.

157
00:07:55,880 --> 00:07:57,350
It's makgeolli.

158
00:07:57,950 --> 00:08:01,189
I spent lots of time thinking about the makgeolli cream.

159
00:08:01,190 --> 00:08:02,950
I'd decided to go with...

160
00:08:03,250 --> 00:08:05,059
the crunchiness of the shell...

161
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:06,520
and the freshness of the makgeolli cream.

162
00:08:07,460 --> 00:08:09,429
As for makgeolli,

163
00:08:09,430 --> 00:08:11,399
I overheard...

164
00:08:11,400 --> 00:08:13,130
that he made it from scratch too.

165
00:08:13,160 --> 00:08:15,970
I thought he came well-prepared.

166
00:08:17,240 --> 00:08:18,939
It'd be disappointing to stop there,

167
00:08:18,940 --> 00:08:21,170
so I'll make it more refreshing with lemon butter.

168
00:08:22,110 --> 00:08:24,310
Cranberry beans, makgeolli,

169
00:08:24,380 --> 00:08:25,609
and lemon zest.

170
00:08:25,610 --> 00:08:26,639
If it goes wrong,

171
00:08:26,640 --> 00:08:28,480
- it'll have the spoiled sour taste. - That's right.

172
00:08:28,580 --> 00:08:30,649
I think the acidity of the lemon...

173
00:08:30,650 --> 00:08:33,890
might turn the sourness into an elegant taste.

174
00:08:40,660 --> 00:08:41,929
- It's pulled sugar. - What?

175
00:08:41,930 --> 00:08:43,460
- It's pulled sugar. - He's pulling sugar.

176
00:08:48,730 --> 00:08:51,640
It's a baking technique called the angel hair technique.

177
00:08:51,770 --> 00:08:53,599
- It's also called pulled hair. - Yes.

178
00:08:53,600 --> 00:08:54,870
He doesn't shake it in the air.

179
00:09:03,510 --> 00:09:05,919
I'll roll the angel hair sugar...

180
00:09:05,920 --> 00:09:07,920
as a platform and decoration.

181
00:09:13,820 --> 00:09:17,060
They've all come up with super complicated recipes.

182
00:09:17,400 --> 00:09:19,199
Is it because it has to be special as it's Round Three?

183
00:09:19,200 --> 00:09:20,930
- Yes. They're so determined. - Yes.

184
00:09:52,600 --> 00:09:55,129
Those two monakas are very different from each other.

185
00:09:55,130 --> 00:09:58,739
Contender Lee Kyung Mu's monaka feels classic and Korean.

186
00:09:58,740 --> 00:10:02,370
They didn't create monaka that we're familiar with.

187
00:10:04,040 --> 00:10:05,510
- They're finally coming. - They're coming.

188
00:10:10,050 --> 00:10:13,419
At first, I came here for fun.

189
00:10:13,420 --> 00:10:17,220
Now that Round Two is over, I really want to win now.

190
00:10:19,960 --> 00:10:22,830
The die has already been cast.

191
00:10:23,090 --> 00:10:24,659
It didn't turn out exactly as I intended,

192
00:10:24,660 --> 00:10:26,299
but it tasted good.

193
00:10:26,300 --> 00:10:28,370
So, I thought it was okay.

194
00:10:31,100 --> 00:10:35,169
Now, what has the classic monaka transformed into?

195
00:10:35,170 --> 00:10:38,680
Contender Lee Kyung Mu will reveal the box first.

196
00:10:45,220 --> 00:10:46,979
- Tiger Monaka Bread. - Tiger Monaka Bread.

197
00:10:46,980 --> 00:10:48,120
It's 3 dollars 20 cents.

198
00:10:48,920 --> 00:10:50,319
It's 3 dollars 20 cents.

199
00:10:50,320 --> 00:10:51,490
It's a reasonable price.

200
00:10:51,590 --> 00:10:53,489
- It's so pretty. It's snowed. - Yes.

201
00:10:53,490 --> 00:10:55,159
Contender Lee Kyung Mu,

202
00:10:55,160 --> 00:10:57,260
will you tell us about your Rebaked Bread?

203
00:10:57,530 --> 00:10:59,800
While maintaining the crunchiness of monaka,

204
00:10:59,900 --> 00:11:03,029
I used Korean ingredients, including cranberry beans...

205
00:11:03,030 --> 00:11:05,339
and makgeolli, the Korean wine,

206
00:11:05,340 --> 00:11:08,669
to reinterpret monaka and create a K-monaka bread.

207
00:11:08,670 --> 00:11:11,339
- It's 3 dollars and 20 cents. - Yes.

208
00:11:11,340 --> 00:11:14,780
You used a special ingredient to lower the price.

209
00:11:14,850 --> 00:11:19,650
The popular sweet paste is red bean paste.

210
00:11:19,720 --> 00:11:24,019
But there's an issue with supply, and it's too mass-produced.

211
00:11:24,020 --> 00:11:27,319
I wanted to make something with the beans from Korea.

212
00:11:27,320 --> 00:11:30,629
I used this opportunity to do that, and got the cranberry beans...

213
00:11:30,630 --> 00:11:32,399
my mother always cultivates.

214
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:35,199
I prepared my recipe while thinking about how to use them.

215
00:11:35,200 --> 00:11:37,639
That's why you used the cranberry beans.

216
00:11:37,640 --> 00:11:38,670
Yes.

217
00:11:39,640 --> 00:11:42,939
Next, it's the Rabaked Bread by Contender Cho Sang Min.

218
00:11:42,940 --> 00:11:44,110
Come and reveal it.

219
00:11:52,920 --> 00:11:55,450
Pouring Monaka. It's 14 dollars.

220
00:11:57,860 --> 00:12:01,059
Now, Contender Cho Sang Min, please tell us about your bread.

221
00:12:01,060 --> 00:12:04,400
As for the dessert I've prepared today,

222
00:12:04,500 --> 00:12:05,829
I reinterpreted...

223
00:12:05,830 --> 00:12:09,300
the classic monaka into a modern plated dessert.

224
00:12:09,470 --> 00:12:11,600
It's a plated dessert...

225
00:12:11,770 --> 00:12:14,239
where you break the chocolate shell of the monaka...

226
00:12:14,240 --> 00:12:18,539
and enjoy the red-bean jelly...

227
00:12:18,540 --> 00:12:19,940
with matcha ice cream.

228
00:12:20,180 --> 00:12:23,249
Its kick is the red bean jelly that pours out from it.

229
00:12:23,250 --> 00:12:27,049
I wanted to give an impression it's pouring out from the shell.

230
00:12:27,050 --> 00:12:29,649
I thought if I made it into jelly,

231
00:12:29,650 --> 00:12:31,219
it'd have a good texture...

232
00:12:31,220 --> 00:12:33,920
and go well with other ingredients.

233
00:12:33,960 --> 00:12:37,960
Okay. We'll try Cho Sang Min's Rebaked Bread now.

234
00:12:39,530 --> 00:12:41,429
How do I eat it?

235
00:12:41,430 --> 00:12:43,199
- Everything at once? - First,

236
00:12:43,200 --> 00:12:46,539
you can break the monaka shell...

237
00:12:46,540 --> 00:12:48,669
coated with chocolate. Then you can enjoy the red bean jelly...

238
00:12:48,670 --> 00:12:52,039
with the ice cream and crumbles beneath it in one bite.

239
00:12:52,040 --> 00:12:53,540
That's the best way to enjoy it.

240
00:12:54,250 --> 00:12:56,280
I see. There's something inside.

241
00:12:58,880 --> 00:13:00,990
This one and... Like this.

242
00:13:13,660 --> 00:13:15,400
There's a real monaka inside.

243
00:13:16,070 --> 00:13:17,970
- Monaka was hiding here. - I know.

244
00:13:38,790 --> 00:13:40,160
It has a diverse texture.

245
00:13:54,840 --> 00:13:58,180
It's 14 dollars. Is there a reason behind that?

246
00:13:58,440 --> 00:14:01,079
Basically, I assumed...

247
00:14:01,080 --> 00:14:04,379
I'd sell it in a hotel...

248
00:14:04,380 --> 00:14:05,980
and decided the price for it.

249
00:14:07,350 --> 00:14:10,889
I've created something...

250
00:14:10,890 --> 00:14:13,959
you can only experience at a hotel,

251
00:14:13,960 --> 00:14:15,830
so that was the price I set.

252
00:14:17,860 --> 00:14:21,229
I was very concerned while he was making it.

253
00:14:21,230 --> 00:14:24,970
"What does this process he is taking..."

254
00:14:25,240 --> 00:14:28,870
"have to do with monaka?"

255
00:14:34,810 --> 00:14:37,720
But after seeing the final product,

256
00:14:38,320 --> 00:14:41,950
I could tell you put lots of thought into it.

257
00:14:42,850 --> 00:14:45,260
As a reinterpretation of monaka,

258
00:14:46,160 --> 00:14:47,830
it was a good one.

259
00:14:49,690 --> 00:14:52,129
I agree with Master Noh Hee Young.

260
00:14:52,130 --> 00:14:56,100
I was worried a lot because of the ice cream.

261
00:14:56,370 --> 00:14:59,899
But it was served at the right temperature.

262
00:14:59,900 --> 00:15:01,910
I was satisfied with that.

263
00:15:04,210 --> 00:15:06,580
But what disappointed me...

264
00:15:10,810 --> 00:15:12,849
was that the plating...

265
00:15:12,850 --> 00:15:16,289
didn't meet the expectation I had...

266
00:15:16,290 --> 00:15:18,290
for the high price.

267
00:15:18,890 --> 00:15:21,629
But in the end, it turned out better than I thought.

268
00:15:21,630 --> 00:15:24,860
It's tastier than expected, so that's great.

269
00:15:24,960 --> 00:15:26,100
I enjoyed it.

270
00:15:26,500 --> 00:15:27,560
Thank you.

271
00:15:28,430 --> 00:15:31,099
I wonder if it'd go as I planned.

272
00:15:31,100 --> 00:15:33,770
I'd say I reached 80 percent.

273
00:15:34,240 --> 00:15:35,540
It's not bad.

274
00:15:36,170 --> 00:15:38,439
I do think he did a good job.

275
00:15:38,440 --> 00:15:40,810
I didn't feel uncomfortable. No.

276
00:15:41,080 --> 00:15:43,010
I wasn't nervous either.

277
00:15:43,280 --> 00:15:47,420
Now, let's try Lee Kyung Mu's Rebaked Bread.

278
00:15:47,550 --> 00:15:50,889
What are these on the side?

279
00:15:50,890 --> 00:15:52,689
- As for the tiger, - Yes.

280
00:15:52,690 --> 00:15:55,589
it's like the one from "KPop Demon Hunters."

281
00:15:55,590 --> 00:15:58,059
- I see. - I wanted to show a tiger.

282
00:15:58,060 --> 00:16:00,530
I portrayed it as a painting of a tiger and magpies.

283
00:16:00,660 --> 00:16:04,570
- I see. - Those are birdtracks.

284
00:16:29,560 --> 00:16:31,630
Gosh. These are cranberry beans.

285
00:16:38,570 --> 00:16:40,300
I got nervous as it was Round Three.

286
00:16:45,310 --> 00:16:46,540
He's a pro.

287
00:16:50,680 --> 00:16:51,680
Gosh.

288
00:16:52,980 --> 00:16:54,990
- Did he make this from makgeolli? - Exactly.

289
00:17:07,500 --> 00:17:11,340
I was super prejudiced when I heard makgeolli's sourness.

290
00:17:11,970 --> 00:17:13,070
"It must be sour."

291
00:17:14,670 --> 00:17:16,510
The sourness from it...

292
00:17:16,710 --> 00:17:19,040
met the subtle sweetness...

293
00:17:19,240 --> 00:17:21,409
of the cranberry beans.

294
00:17:21,410 --> 00:17:22,849
Then the chocolate burst in my mouth.

295
00:17:22,850 --> 00:17:25,680
It was crunchy too. It was the texture I've never had.

296
00:17:26,080 --> 00:17:27,720
Everything felt so diverse.

297
00:17:27,820 --> 00:17:30,689
Personally, as a consumer,

298
00:17:30,690 --> 00:17:32,120
this was the tastiest one I had so far.

299
00:17:32,720 --> 00:17:34,190
I liked it the most.

300
00:17:35,290 --> 00:17:36,730
I found it so interesting.

301
00:17:37,090 --> 00:17:39,330
It doesn't look like monaka at all.

302
00:17:40,600 --> 00:17:44,100
But when I eat it, it has the familiar taste of monaka.

303
00:17:44,230 --> 00:17:46,070
I think...

304
00:17:46,300 --> 00:17:50,740
it's all thanks to the cranberry beans.

305
00:17:50,840 --> 00:17:54,239
Overall, there were many flavors, including sourness.

306
00:17:54,240 --> 00:17:58,949
And the cranberry beans embraced everything together in a gentle way.

307
00:17:58,950 --> 00:18:02,650
So I could enjoy the light taste until the end.

308
00:18:04,050 --> 00:18:06,190
I thought it was a matter of course.

309
00:18:07,290 --> 00:18:09,689
I wanted to taste it...

310
00:18:09,690 --> 00:18:11,030
to see how great it is.

311
00:18:12,200 --> 00:18:16,500
When I judge for a competition, what I find the hardest is...

312
00:18:16,630 --> 00:18:19,039
whether to give points to one's creativity...

313
00:18:19,040 --> 00:18:20,399
or its commercial value.

314
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:23,469
I'm the one who considers both of them.

315
00:18:23,470 --> 00:18:25,409
When there are lemon and cream cheese already,

316
00:18:25,410 --> 00:18:28,509
you added sour makgeolli cream on top of that.

317
00:18:28,510 --> 00:18:30,379
Is that a plus?

318
00:18:30,380 --> 00:18:33,280
Or is it just redundant? That's the issue.

319
00:18:36,590 --> 00:18:39,090
Being less would have been better.

320
00:18:41,690 --> 00:18:44,559
As for the reinterpretation of monaka,

321
00:18:44,560 --> 00:18:48,030
I loved that you made the shell with the pie dough.

322
00:18:48,300 --> 00:18:50,570
But there's a taste that bothers me.

323
00:18:51,570 --> 00:18:52,600
It's makgeolli.

324
00:18:54,540 --> 00:18:55,670
It wasn't to my taste.

325
00:18:56,640 --> 00:18:59,879
Cream cheese is a bit sour. And makgeolli is sour.

326
00:18:59,880 --> 00:19:02,110
And the aftertaste is...

327
00:19:02,250 --> 00:19:05,450
Only the taste of makgeolli is left on my tongue in the end.

328
00:19:07,180 --> 00:19:10,150
What if you didn't add makgeolli?

329
00:19:14,090 --> 00:19:17,430
Gosh. I was a bit disappointed.

330
00:19:17,960 --> 00:19:21,899
Okay. It's time to make your decision.

331
00:19:21,900 --> 00:19:24,130
Let's check the result...

332
00:19:24,600 --> 00:19:26,300
of the monaka's transformation.

333
00:19:27,170 --> 00:19:30,310
Who will be the winner of the 1-on-1 Deathmatch?

334
00:19:31,710 --> 00:19:32,740
Please reveal the result.

335
00:19:34,550 --> 00:19:36,680
I really had no idea.

336
00:19:37,750 --> 00:19:40,249
"I'm pretty sure that I did slightly better than him."

337
00:19:40,250 --> 00:19:41,690
Such a thought did cross my mind.

338
00:19:57,300 --> 00:19:59,400
The winner is Contender Lee Kyung Mu.

339
00:19:59,970 --> 00:20:02,670
You've made it to the semifinal round.

340
00:20:02,940 --> 00:20:06,440
I think the popular term "K-Bread" is the key to my victory.

341
00:20:06,810 --> 00:20:08,579
I think reinterpreting monaka as a Korean style bread...

342
00:20:08,580 --> 00:20:12,320
really resonated with the Masters.

343
00:20:12,820 --> 00:20:15,619
Contender Cho Sang Min, it's sad,

344
00:20:15,620 --> 00:20:18,090
but your journey on Bake Your Dreams ends here.

345
00:20:18,690 --> 00:20:20,119
- I appreciate your efforts. - Thank you.

346
00:20:20,120 --> 00:20:21,389
- You did a great job. - Thank you.

347
00:20:21,390 --> 00:20:23,959
Please share your feelings...

348
00:20:23,960 --> 00:20:25,360
about competing against each other.

349
00:20:25,500 --> 00:20:26,559
It was an enjoyable match...

350
00:20:26,560 --> 00:20:29,369
as we were able to connect to each other through bread...

351
00:20:29,370 --> 00:20:30,600
regardless of age.

352
00:20:31,900 --> 00:20:33,099
Although I failed to move up,

353
00:20:33,100 --> 00:20:35,639
I viewed all the Masters' feedback...

354
00:20:35,640 --> 00:20:37,769
as constructive and took it to heart.

355
00:20:37,770 --> 00:20:41,239
And while competing against him, I learned a lot.

356
00:20:41,240 --> 00:20:42,310
I'm grateful to him for that.

357
00:20:43,010 --> 00:20:44,780
- You did a great job. - Thank you.

358
00:20:59,260 --> 00:21:02,300
I'd be lying if I said I wasn't sad.

359
00:21:03,600 --> 00:21:05,170
If I had only made it to the top ten,

360
00:21:06,100 --> 00:21:08,610
I would be proud to talk about this experience.

361
00:21:09,710 --> 00:21:11,980
I realized once again that competition is always cutthroat.

362
00:21:13,310 --> 00:21:16,450
If I were given another chance, I would love to try again.

363
00:21:19,520 --> 00:21:20,680
I would do a better job then.

364
00:21:33,430 --> 00:21:34,900
It's not over yet.

365
00:21:40,170 --> 00:21:42,539
You will be given the last chance...

366
00:21:42,540 --> 00:21:44,310
to continue your journey on this show.

367
00:21:44,710 --> 00:21:46,010
The final 16 contenders?

368
00:21:46,210 --> 00:21:48,450
I don't think anyone will remember us.

369
00:21:49,150 --> 00:21:50,750
I told myself to survive with determination.

370
00:21:51,480 --> 00:21:53,950
Honestly, I didn't think I'd end up in the Repechage.

371
00:21:54,750 --> 00:21:56,220
This is an opportunity for me.

372
00:21:57,790 --> 00:21:59,820
The mission for the Repechage will be revealed.

373
00:22:07,130 --> 00:22:08,970
You have 30 minutes...

374
00:22:09,200 --> 00:22:11,130
to complete your no-oven baking...

375
00:22:11,540 --> 00:22:13,870
using only the ingredients found in the fridge.

376
00:22:17,770 --> 00:22:18,840
No-oven baking?

377
00:22:20,040 --> 00:22:21,680
We have a lot of ovens here,

378
00:22:21,980 --> 00:22:23,150
but we can't use any of them?

379
00:22:23,710 --> 00:22:26,650
It's a very short amount of time for baking, in a sense.

380
00:22:26,720 --> 00:22:28,590
But we wanted to see...

381
00:22:29,120 --> 00:22:32,290
how you brought out your abilities and creativity...

382
00:22:32,760 --> 00:22:34,830
under such a tight deadline.

383
00:22:35,730 --> 00:22:37,190
Based on my experience,

384
00:22:37,430 --> 00:22:39,729
your brain doesn't function properly at this point.

385
00:22:39,730 --> 00:22:40,860
And you must be exhausted.

386
00:22:41,600 --> 00:22:42,970
I hope you can overcome it...

387
00:22:43,330 --> 00:22:45,070
and try something new that you don't usually do.

388
00:22:45,470 --> 00:22:48,110
This is your chance to showcase your own unique idea.

389
00:22:48,370 --> 00:22:51,440
I believe it's rather a great opportunity.

390
00:22:52,480 --> 00:22:55,150
The number of the contenders to survive the Repechage is...

391
00:22:56,950 --> 00:22:58,050
two.

392
00:23:00,680 --> 00:23:02,420
Now,

393
00:23:03,520 --> 00:23:04,890
please start...

394
00:23:08,830 --> 00:23:09,890
baking your dreams.

395
00:23:11,630 --> 00:23:12,659
You've got this!

396
00:23:12,660 --> 00:23:13,660
- You've got this! - The Repechage has begun.

397
00:23:13,661 --> 00:23:16,069
- You've got this! - The Repechage has begun.

398
00:23:16,070 --> 00:23:17,400
- Go for it! - You've got this!

399
00:23:18,570 --> 00:23:20,070
You must run. You don't have much time.

400
00:23:20,340 --> 00:23:21,640
You have only 30 minutes.

401
00:23:25,510 --> 00:23:26,779
- They must be nervous. - My gosh.

402
00:23:26,780 --> 00:23:29,050
- This is unbelievable. - I'm so relieved.

403
00:23:29,180 --> 00:23:30,279
They have to wrap it up only in 30 minutes.

404
00:23:30,280 --> 00:23:32,149
It's already tough to bake with the ingredients on hand,

405
00:23:32,150 --> 00:23:33,279
- Exactly. - and now they have to improvise...

406
00:23:33,280 --> 00:23:34,450
with what they find in the fridge.

407
00:23:34,620 --> 00:23:35,789
- That's right. - They have to move around.

408
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:36,890
They're looking for what they need.

409
00:23:37,990 --> 00:23:39,220
Thirty minutes fly by in the blink of an eye.

410
00:23:39,860 --> 00:23:41,930
And it's over for them once they make a mistake.

411
00:23:42,260 --> 00:23:44,659
I think it's important to come up with an idea quickly.

412
00:23:44,660 --> 00:23:45,660
Really?

413
00:23:51,740 --> 00:23:53,740
- Sang Min returned quickly. - He's starting right away.

414
00:23:54,500 --> 00:23:56,170
He's ahead of everyone else right now.

415
00:24:04,150 --> 00:24:06,150
He's running. I've never seen him run before.

416
00:24:07,220 --> 00:24:08,989
They have no choice but to run since they have only 30 minutes.

417
00:24:08,990 --> 00:24:10,720
You're right. They have no choice but to run.

418
00:24:11,220 --> 00:24:12,360
This is their last chance.

419
00:24:15,790 --> 00:24:17,860
Many of them are using cream cheese.

420
00:24:18,360 --> 00:24:19,760
Sang Min is using cream cheese.

421
00:24:20,430 --> 00:24:21,630
And Yeoju Natural Man.

422
00:24:23,200 --> 00:24:25,040
I'm curious about Contender Oh Seung Geun's product.

423
00:24:25,240 --> 00:24:27,240
I wonder what kind of bread he'll make within 30 minutes.

424
00:24:27,940 --> 00:24:30,769
- This is a wild card round. - Yes.

425
00:24:30,770 --> 00:24:32,639
They shouldn't do what they usually do.

426
00:24:32,640 --> 00:24:34,080
For a mission with a short time limit like this,

427
00:24:34,140 --> 00:24:35,810
you need to predict what the others will make too.

428
00:24:36,650 --> 00:24:37,810
But not many people...

429
00:24:38,380 --> 00:24:40,080
can be bold enough to take a risk in a wild card round.

430
00:24:40,350 --> 00:24:42,790
It's understandable because they're all desperate.

431
00:24:44,890 --> 00:24:46,790
I'm really curious how their creations turn out.

432
00:24:49,130 --> 00:24:50,490
She's using sausages.

433
00:24:51,830 --> 00:24:54,529
It seems that Contender Hwang Ji Oh chose sausages.

434
00:24:54,530 --> 00:24:55,569
- Sausages? - Yes.

435
00:24:55,570 --> 00:24:56,729
That's a good idea.

436
00:24:56,730 --> 00:24:59,740
The salty flavor will work in her favor.

437
00:24:59,840 --> 00:25:01,810
Everyone else seems to be making something sweet.

438
00:25:02,840 --> 00:25:05,340
Salty and spicy food is perfect at this hour.

439
00:25:06,640 --> 00:25:08,380
Sausages sound delicious.

440
00:25:10,680 --> 00:25:13,250
Oh, my goodness. What's that? What is it?

441
00:25:14,080 --> 00:25:15,620
A mixture of orange juice and jelly?

442
00:25:18,960 --> 00:25:22,190
I wanted to utilize the properties of jelly.

443
00:25:22,830 --> 00:25:26,460
I think he'll be using it as a sauce.

444
00:25:27,560 --> 00:25:28,669
Using jelly instead of gelatine...

445
00:25:28,670 --> 00:25:31,029
- is a very good idea. - I agree. It's a great idea.

446
00:25:31,030 --> 00:25:32,270
- He can save time. - Right.

447
00:25:35,610 --> 00:25:36,840
Five minutes have already passed.

448
00:25:38,170 --> 00:25:39,310
It just began.

449
00:25:40,510 --> 00:25:41,650
Time is flying by so quickly.

450
00:25:42,550 --> 00:25:44,380
Gosh. This is crazy.

451
00:25:44,950 --> 00:25:47,680
To be honest, I don't mind not using an oven.

452
00:25:48,250 --> 00:25:50,550
But I have only 30 minutes, which is a tight window.

453
00:25:51,150 --> 00:25:53,690
And that makes the recipe simple.

454
00:25:54,460 --> 00:25:58,130
The first thing that crossed my mind was a no-oven cheesecake.

455
00:26:04,330 --> 00:26:05,700
Is that scorched rice?

456
00:26:06,440 --> 00:26:09,569
I wanted to add a unique highlight to a simple recipe.

457
00:26:09,570 --> 00:26:12,310
So I made something like rice gelato.

458
00:26:14,410 --> 00:26:15,950
Wait. He's using instant rice?

459
00:26:24,220 --> 00:26:25,390
He'll mix it with that?

460
00:26:26,160 --> 00:26:27,320
With cream cheese?

461
00:26:29,960 --> 00:26:33,060
Maybe he's making it like rice pudding.

462
00:26:34,200 --> 00:26:35,970
It seems a bit of a risky move.

463
00:26:42,810 --> 00:26:43,910
A steamer?

464
00:26:44,270 --> 00:26:45,380
- He's steaming something? - A steamer?

465
00:26:45,910 --> 00:26:48,650
I don't think he has enough time to use a steamer.

466
00:26:48,950 --> 00:26:50,250
I have absolutely no idea.

467
00:26:51,210 --> 00:26:53,479
But steaming is faster than baking.

468
00:26:53,480 --> 00:26:54,480
Is that so?

469
00:26:55,090 --> 00:26:56,920
A steamer is the second fastest, after a microwave.

470
00:27:01,090 --> 00:27:04,329
Since it wasn't something that I had expertise in,

471
00:27:04,330 --> 00:27:05,700
I was very worried.

472
00:27:09,130 --> 00:27:11,230
I tried to come up with the simplest recipe possible,

473
00:27:11,740 --> 00:27:16,070
and I decided to reinterpret the old-fashioned steamed bread.

474
00:27:16,970 --> 00:27:18,380
I put a lot of cheese in it.

475
00:27:19,910 --> 00:27:21,710
I put melted cheese inside the dough.

476
00:27:21,980 --> 00:27:24,810
I added Gouda and rolled cheese inside...

477
00:27:24,950 --> 00:27:27,020
and then topped it with parmesan cheese.

478
00:27:27,950 --> 00:27:30,350
A moist texture and sweet and salty flavors.

479
00:27:30,690 --> 00:27:33,260
I focused on those three elements.

480
00:27:36,890 --> 00:27:39,399
Since he's steaming his bread,

481
00:27:39,400 --> 00:27:40,630
there's nothing more he can do to perfect it.

482
00:27:41,460 --> 00:27:42,570
Now, all he can do is pray.

483
00:27:44,470 --> 00:27:45,800
Ten minutes have passed already.

484
00:27:46,640 --> 00:27:47,970
Gosh. Ten minutes have flown by.

485
00:27:58,210 --> 00:27:59,420
- She's using 2 frying pans, not 1? - Yes.

486
00:28:00,120 --> 00:28:01,220
She really is skillful.

487
00:28:03,420 --> 00:28:04,690
What kind of batter is that?

488
00:28:07,490 --> 00:28:08,890
Is she making crepe?

489
00:28:09,260 --> 00:28:10,290
I think so.

490
00:28:10,390 --> 00:28:13,460
Crepes are the quickest thing you can make.

491
00:28:13,660 --> 00:28:15,930
That's right. They're thin.

492
00:28:16,330 --> 00:28:18,600
Crepes cool down instantly once they leave the pan.

493
00:28:18,740 --> 00:28:20,070
That's right, because they're thin.

494
00:28:20,200 --> 00:28:21,810
That allows you to shape it right away.

495
00:28:22,740 --> 00:28:25,880
I scanned the provided ingredients.

496
00:28:26,140 --> 00:28:28,379
And I saw a lot of good ingredients...

497
00:28:28,380 --> 00:28:30,780
I could use to make a savory dish.

498
00:28:31,180 --> 00:28:34,419
So I decided to make a bread with the ultimate balance...

499
00:28:34,420 --> 00:28:36,350
of sweet and salty flavors that you can enjoy in one bite.

500
00:28:39,760 --> 00:28:42,230
I decided to go with water frying...

501
00:28:42,790 --> 00:28:46,500
to let the aroma of the sausages fill the entire studio.

502
00:28:48,770 --> 00:28:50,970
What is this grilling smell?

503
00:28:51,630 --> 00:28:52,800
Oh, my. I can smell the sausages.

504
00:28:53,640 --> 00:28:54,870
The sausages smell so great.

505
00:28:55,570 --> 00:29:00,410
I thought it could make the Masters feel hungry.

506
00:29:09,790 --> 00:29:11,120
Contender Oh Seung Geun is done.

507
00:29:13,860 --> 00:29:15,020
I'm done.

508
00:29:16,030 --> 00:29:17,060
He finished in just ten minutes.

509
00:29:18,060 --> 00:29:19,230
Is it even possible?

510
00:29:19,730 --> 00:29:21,060
What did he make?

511
00:29:21,230 --> 00:29:22,970
The dish I made for the Repechage was...

512
00:29:23,130 --> 00:29:24,770
Banana Tiramisu.

513
00:29:25,370 --> 00:29:28,769
Since I had a lot of experience making tiramisu,

514
00:29:28,770 --> 00:29:30,339
I was familiar with its characteristics,

515
00:29:30,340 --> 00:29:32,080
which made it easy for me to handle the ingredients.

516
00:29:33,110 --> 00:29:34,180
Oh, my. That's amazing.

517
00:29:34,940 --> 00:29:38,310
I felt confident while I was making it,

518
00:29:38,450 --> 00:29:40,180
but when I looked around me, I was surprised.

519
00:29:42,320 --> 00:29:45,389
Many of them were going with complex recipes.

520
00:29:45,390 --> 00:29:46,690
I was taken aback.

521
00:29:52,930 --> 00:29:55,930
It must be perfect.

522
00:30:07,140 --> 00:30:09,350
Where is this sweet aroma coming from?

523
00:30:09,810 --> 00:30:10,810
It's Min Su.

524
00:30:11,610 --> 00:30:12,820
He's caramelizing apples.

525
00:30:14,220 --> 00:30:15,249
